Date: Fri 16 Feb 2001 11:43:47 -0500
From: Dean L. Smith <SmithDL3@state.gov>

Support for a "Pan-global" Vaccine
----------------------------------
I read Dr. Woodall's recent post [Influenza vaccine: time for global unity?
20010210.0268 with great interest, as I am also struggling with the
northern-southern hemisphere influenza vaccine issue. I am a regional
medical officer with the US Department of State posted in Lima, Peru and I
cover the northern tier of the South American continent. My patients, the
diplomatic staff of the State Department, are at high risk of contracting
influenza during both peaks, i.e., December-February and May-July. As you
are aware, the vaccines for the hemispheres do not provide
"cross-coverage"; hence we are currently vaccinating twice yearly.
Needless to say, this is not met with a great deal of enthusiasm by our
patients or by our Health Units, who must procure, administer and monitor
these vaccines. I share your interest in the development of a unified, once
yearly "pan-global" [global vaccine.
--
Dean Smith, MD
Regional Medical Officer
US Embassy Lima
Lima, Peru
<smithdl3@state.gov>
[Influenza virus vaccines as presently formulated induce diminished
responses in elderly recipients and the availability of a global vaccine
might still necessitate twice-yearly vaccination. - Mods.JW/CP
