[2
Date: Tue 13 Feb 2001 10:05:12 -0700
From: Hal Nash <HNASH@wwcc.cc.wy.us>

An Alternative Perspective
--------------------------
I am curious as to the seminal thought that led to distinctions between
northern and southern hemispheric varieties [of influenza virus. It is
obvious that actual geography does not obey the arbitrary lines drawn on
the planet by mankind... nor do infectious disease agents care much for
lines drawn for navigational purposes. Dr. Jack Woodall's initial post in
this thread is the first I've ever read of such a man-made geographical
distinction being used to define the range of an infectious agent.
Perhaps the explanation lies in the shortcomings of human language. It may
be easier to speak of northern and southern hemispheres than continents
(separated by water) and regions (separated by physical features such as
large rivers, mountains, and inhospitable environments: deserts and ice).
Nevertheless, I find the "north-south" designation quite arbitrary,
potentially vague, possibly misleading, and definitely confusing.
Scientific language provides for precise, definitive descriptions. If
anyone could provide a rationale for such a distinction, I would be
interested in reading it.
--
Hal B. Nash
Assistant Professor of Biology
Western Wyoming College
Rock Springs, WY 82901
<hnash@wwcc.cc.wy.us>
